x4freetext: Experiment performed using neutron
beam at LANSCE, Los Alamos National Laboratory,
produced by spallation of 800 MeV protons
Target-1
Highly enriched 236U target with mass of 20.4 mg
used for most of the beam time
Target-2
with mass 10 mg
The purpose of using Target-2 was to validate the
ratio method with the different reaction rates of
Target-3
with mass 10 mg
The purpose of using Target-3 was to measure the
ratio of reaction rates N(236U(n,g))/N(235U(n,f))
Target-4
with mass 100 mu-g
Thin electroplated target used to define the
Using Target-4 the 236U(n,g) cross section for the
resonances at 5.45 and 43.91 eV was determined relative
to the 235U(n,f) cross section at 8.76 and 35.18 eV
The final result of the cross section was determined
from the Target-1 and Target-3 data normalized to the
absolute value of the cross section from the Target-4.
Gamma rays were detected using DANCE array
consists of 160 BaF2 scintillator crystals in a
closed 4Pi geometry. The BaF2 crystal has fast (0.6 ns)
and slow (600 ns) scintillation light output
components. The fast timing of the scintillators
leads to a precise determination of the neutron time
of flight and a good identification of coincident
gamma rays following neutron capture.
Incident neutron energy was determined by time
of flight method.
The neutron beam at LANSCE is produced by the
spallation reaction of 800 MeV accelerated protons
irradiating a tungsten target and is moderated in a
water moderator. The neutron energy is calculated
based on the flight time, a 20.28 m flight path
length, and a 523 ns delay time after the T0 pulse,
generated when the proton bunch hits the tungsten
target.
